entry.title: Fix WebGPU resource destruction race condition
entry.content:
Problem: When tearing down a web page that uses WebGPU in a worker, the

order of garbage collection between the placeholder canvas and the

worker thread is non-deterministic. This means that it may not be

possible to return the CanvasResource held by the placeholder canvas

back to the thread where it was created. The problem with this is that

the ExternalCanvasResource objects used by WebGPU may hold a

viz::ReleaseCallback object, which is not thread safe. Even though the

callback is never called on the wrong thread, simply destroying it on

the wrong thread causes problems because objects bound to the callback

closure may end up being unref'ed and destroyed on the wrong thread.



The solution implemented in this CL avoids transiting the

viz::ReleaseCallback through other threads, which guarantees it will

never be destroyed on the wrong thread. We basically detach the

release callback from the CanvasResource before dispatching it to the

placeholder canvas (on the main thread), and we re-attach the callback

when the resource is returned to its thread of origin (for final

destruction or recycling).



Bug: 1426480

entry.title: [rust] supersize fix for invalid utf8
entry.content:
Rust third-party packages ("crates") have descriptions and author names

which may contain non-ASCII text. Some Rust language features make those

strings available in the build so that they can be presented in help

text, etc. Therefore our gn build rules pass them into ninja.



For the non-ASCII case, gn writes invalid UTF8 to the ninja file. It

appears that the gn function EscapeStringToString_PosixNinjaFork will

require significant rework in order to write non-ASCII text correctly.



Meanwhile, to unblock Rust project progress, make supersize robust

against these errors.

entry.title: Record shutdown-hang related times
entry.content:
When investigating shutdown hangs it can be important to know key times

like when shutdown started, when a particular task was started, and when

a shutdown hang was detected. Previously this information was difficult

to obtain but this change puts these three times in local variables in

the appropriate threads, using base::debug::Alias() to lock them there.



This allows determining, for instance, how long the shutdown-hang

timeout was, and whether a task was started before or after shutdown was

initiated.

entry.title: Configure randomized response rates in terms of epsilon
entry.content:
This CL modifies the AttributionConfig to use the randomized response

epsilon level as a parameter instead of specific event/navigation

randomized response rates. Interop tests configs are updated accordingly.



This epsilon parameter is used to dynamically compute the RR rates at

runtime, as a function of the number of possible output states in each

source type variant.



For now this is hard-coded, but in a follow-up the number of output

states will be made dynamic based on the event_report_window parameter.



This CL has a few observable behavior changes. Now that we compute RR

rates dynamically we no longer apply ad-hoc rounding when computing the

`randomized_trigger_rate` for a source. This means that:

1. We actually apply a very slightly higher RR rate for nav sources

and slightly lower RR rate for event sources.

navigation sources: .0024 --> 0.002426322167...

event sources: .0.0000025 --> 0.000002494582...



2. The `randomized_trigger_rate` field in event-level reports is

uniformly rounded to 7 decimal places across both event and

navigation sources.



Bug: 1434755

entry.title: input_injector_wayland: Fix libei session tear down
entry.content:
We want to stop injecting inputs when we don't have

the screencast stream/virtual monitor. We already

do this by registering Core class's shutdown callbakc

that gets triggered by the desktop capturer cleanup.

We were also calling this cleanup again when the

injector is getting destroyed - this is redundant

and is removed in the patch.



Other changes:

- Ensures that the cleanup (now renamed

as shutdown) in the remote desktop portal injector

module happens on the same thread to which the object

was bound initially. Before this change the could

have been done on any thread where this object was

destroyed.



- Fixes the cleanup order in the

event watcher module where we close the file

descriptor before destroying the source. This is

followed by unref-ing the `ei` handle. This setup

now is similar to how mutter does its main loop

event cleanup for `libeis`.



- Improves the state machine of the injector by

making the states more explicit and ensuring the

transitions happen in a sequence.



- Removes an unused method (i.e. `InjectScrollWheelClicks`)

entry.title: [CodeHealth] Fix UnsafeDanglingUntriaged in BackgroundContentsService
entry.content:
This CL is part of a larger cleanup effort to triage dangling pointers

and ensure they aren't the cause of memory issues in Chrome. See:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/164SnySRX6MZgFkX8qLLLClTnZ0S8s5wLiNFWNyQ8f4E/edit



`ShowBalloon` binds a raw pointer to Profile when creating a callback

passed to `NotificationImageReady`. But this Profile can be destroyed

before the callback gets called.



This CL handles this situation by:

1) Adding a dependency on NotificationDisplayService in

BackgroundContentsServiceFactory to ensure the

NotificationDisplayService doesn't get destroyed

before the BackgroundContentsService.

2) Converting ShowBalloon and NotificationImageReady from

free functions to private members of BackgroundContentsService

3) Binding a WeakPtr to BackgroundContentsService in the callback

created in ShowBallon.



This CL also removes the CommandLine* argument passed to the

constructor of BackgroundContentsService, since this is unused.

entry.title: [balance-text] Fix break token propagation
entry.content:
When crrev.com/c/4369820 tried to move `PropagatedBreakTokens`

out of `NGLineBreaker`, it did:

1. Move propagated break tokens while line breaking to

`NGLineInfo`.

2. Move propagated break tokens while `CreateLine` to

`NGInlineChildLayoutContext`.



2 was not correct, because the algorithm may retry not only

line breaking but also `CreateLine` in certain cases, and

propagated break tokens from non-final `CreateLine` should not

be added to `NGInlineChildLayoutContext`.



This patch fixes this by changing `CreateLine` to add

propagated break tokens to `NGLineInfo`, and move them to

`NGInlineChildLayoutContext` only if the line layout is final.

entry.title: Introduce WarmUpServiceWorker
entry.content:
This CL introduces WarmUpServiceWorker function which warms-up Service

Workers. WarmUpServiceWorker prepares the renderer process, initializes

mojo pipes, and loads top-level scripts without evaluating the Service

Worker's top-level script.



[How warmed-up Service Worker behaves]



After the service worker is warmed-up, the running_status() will be kept

as `STARTING` status.



There are the following scenarios after Service Worker is warmed-up.



A) Time out (after kWarmUpDuration) => Service Worker will stop.

B) Be requested to warm-up again => Extend the time out.

C) Be requested to start => Call `InitializeGlobalScope`.



[How WarmUpServiceWorker works]



WarmUpServiceWorker postpones initializing the global scope. This is

controlled by pause_initializing_global_scope_ flag and

SetPauseInitializingGlobalScope() and ResumeInitializingGlobalScope()

functions.



The following trace logs demonstrate how WarmUpServiceWorker behaves.





https://ui.perfetto.dev/#!/?s=360cc921e9f9563a26de4e7a627bc9fe8ce3bdccf7798f4d372ba71581b16313





https://ui.perfetto.dev/#!/?s=76d3599d825e37c66797380c2696f34d9166e513e998d59d47c4cd99314cb55a



[History of InitializeGlobalScope (delayed global scope initialization)]



In the past, ServiceWorker::InitializeGlobalScope mojo API was used to

prevent from evaluating a script until the byte-for-byte comparison or

COEP check is completed (https://crrev.com/c/2060446). However, this is

not needed after off-the-main-thread service worker script

fetch. PlzServiceWorker CL (https://crrev.com/c/3382976) also cleaned up

the delayed global scope initialization code. Now this CL utilizes the

delayed global scope initialization mechanism to implement

WarmUpServiceWorker.

entry.title: arc: Add ArcExternalStorageAccess feature
entry.content:
The feature allows developers to control access to external storage

devices (e.g. USB flash drives, SD cards) by Android apps. It is enabled

by default, and when it's disabled, mounting events of external storage

devices are blocked by ArcVolumeMounterBridge and not propagated to ARC.



Note that unmounting events are no-op but still propagated to ARC just

to make the behavior aligned with the ExternalStorageDisabled policy;

the policy can be changed runtime and thus it's reasonable to propagate

unmounting events to ARC to make sure things are properly cleaned up.



At the moment, the feature lacks proper UI integration. For example,

even when it's disabled, external drives will still be displayed in the

Files app when opened by Android apps, Android apps will be suggested

when the user tries to open a file in an external drive from the Files

app, etc. However, it should be acceptable for a feature behind a flag.

entry.title: [GPU] Add feature to crash on context loss when running ANGLE in-process
entry.content:
When the GPU service is running in the host process, it does not exit

on context loss even when it otherwise would. However, context loss when

Chrome/WebView are running with WebView is currently not recoverable:

there would need to be a termination and re-initialization of GL, which

Chrome doesn't do. This means that such a context loss will almost

certainly result in a loop of re-initializing and losing contexts,

causing undefined behavior and a likely eventual browser crash.



This CL adds functionality to have the GPU service immediately crash

when running in-process with ANGLE if asked to restart due to a backend

context loss (note that we *don't* do this on synthetic context loss

events generated by Chrome, as these *are* recoverable). We will monitor

the impact on crash rate to determine if we need to invest in making

context loss recoverable in this situation (it won't necessarily have a

significant impact on crash rate: as we noted above, this flow is likely

already resulting in eventual app crashes).



The new behavior is gated by a disabled-by-default Finch flag, so this

CL will not in of itself change any behavior.



Bug: 1432913

entry.title: [compile hints] Fix deps around blink core
entry.content:
The buildflag header added recently in blink/renderer/bindings takes

part in some less obvious parts of the build, deps-wise, and made it

so several compiles could flake in a clean build, such as:

obj/third_party/blink/renderer/core/core_hot/document.o

obj/third_party/blink/renderer/core/animation/animation/animation_timeline.o

obj/third_party/blink/renderer/core/exported/exported/web_document.o

(and more from core/core_hot, core/animation, core/exported).



In the core_hot example, the error looks like this:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/renderer/core/dom/document.cc:129:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/renderer/core/dom/context_features.h:32:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/renderer/core/page/page.h:44:

../../third_party/blink/renderer/bindings/core/v8/v8_compile_hints.h:8:10:

fatal error: 'third_party/blink/renderer/bindings/buildflags.h' file not found



Fix by (1) adding the dep in core_generated, which most relevant targets

already depend on, and (2) adding the dep separately in core_hot,

because that doesn't use core_generated and I'm not sure if it should,
